1 Backgrounds and Objectives

The relationship between obesity and diet is very close. London region faces a very serious threat of obesity. It is great significance to study the distribution of obesity and diet in different London regions to suggest some sensible dietary changes. Therfore, We will first visualiseobesity and dietin different London regions to better understand the relationship between obesity and diet in the city.

3 Data Analysis

3.1 Spatial autocorrelation

Spatial dependence between different London ward is very important for observations of obseity distribution. Spatial autocorrelation occurs when these wards are not independent of one another and instead cluster together across geographic space. In other words, it quantifies the degree of which objects are similar to nearby objects. Variables are said to have a positive spatial autocorrelation when similar values tend to be closer together than dissimilar values. Waldo Tober’s first law of geography is that “Everything is related to everything else, but near things are more related than distant things.” so we would expect most geographic phenomena to exert a spatial autocorrelation of some kind. Here we firstly performed Global Moran’s I method to measure how “random” the spatial distribution of these values is. And secondly, Local Moran’s Imethod is also used.

# convert to sp
MSOA_obesity_diet_sp <- as_Spatial(MSOA_obesity_diet, IDs=MSOA_obesity_diet$area_id)
# inspect
class(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp)
## [1] "SpatialPolygonsDataFrame"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "sp"

3.1.1 Global Moran’s I

We can represent spatial autocorrelation in two ways; globally or locally. Global models will create a single measure to represent the entire study area, whilst local models let us explore how spatial clustering varies across space.
Global Moran’s I is a metric between -1 and 1. -1 is a completely even spatial distribution of values, 0 is a “random” distribution, and 1 is a “non-random” distribution of clearly defined clusters.
library(spdep)

# Calculate neighbours, create an nb object
MSOA_obesity_diet_sp_nb <- poly2nb(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp, row.names=MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$area_id)

# inspect

## Weights style: W 
## Weights constants summary:
##      n       nn   S0       S1       S2
## W 6881 47348161 6881 2231.655 27525.49

Inference for Moran’s I is based on a null hypothesis of spatial randomness. The distribution of the statistic under the null can be derived using either an assumption of normality (independent normal random variates), or so-called randomization (i.e., each value is equally likely to occur at any location).

# Moran's I
mi_value <- moran(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$obesity_ratio,nb_weights_list,n=length(nb_weights_list$neighbours),S0=Szero(nb_weights_list))

# inspect
mi_value 
## $I
## [1] 0.9953213
## 
## $K
## [1] 2.043046
# global spatial autocorrelation
moran.test(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$obesity_ratio,nb_weights_list)
## 
##  Moran I test under randomisation
## 
## data:  MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$obesity_ratio  
## weights: nb_weights_list    
## 
## Moran I statistic standard deviate = 145.05, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
##      9.953213e-01     -1.453488e-04      4.709717e-05

NOTE: The moran I statistic is 0.995, we can therefore determine that there obesity_ratio variable is positively autocorrelated in London. In other words, the data does spatially cluster. We can also consider the p-value to consider the statistical significance of the mode.

Furthermore, we can do this by using something called a Monte Carlo simulation.

# run a Monte Carlo simulation 599 times
mc_model <- moran.mc(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$obesity_ratio, nb_weights_list, nsim=599)  
mc_model
## 
##  Monte-Carlo simulation of Moran I
## 
## data:  MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$obesity_ratio 
## weights: nb_weights_list  
## number of simulations + 1: 600 
## 
## statistic = 0.99532, observed rank = 600, p-value = 0.001667
## alternative hypothesis: greater

NOTE: This model shows that our distribution of obesity_ratio do differs significantly from a random distribution. As such, we can conclude that there is existing global spatial autocorrelation in our data set.

3.1.2 Local Moran’s I

We will first create a moran plot which looks at each of the values plotted against their spatially lagged values. It basically explores the relationship between the data and their neighbours as a scatter plot.
# creates a moran plot
moran <- moran.plot(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$obesity_ratio, listw = nb2listw(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp_nb, style = "W"),asp=T)

#Is it possible to determine a positive relationship from observing the scatter plot.

With a measurement of local spatial autocorrelation we could find hotspots of new case identified that are surrounded by areas of much lower case. According to the previous global statistic these are not randomly distributed pockets but would be outliers against the general trend of clusteredness! These could be areas that contain very specific locations, where interventions could be made that drastically reduce the rate of crime rather than other areas where there is a high level of obesity.

# create an nb object

MSOA_obesity_diet_sp_nb <- poly2nb(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp, row.names=MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$area_id)

# create the list weights object
nb_weights_list <- nb2listw(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp_nb, style='W')

# Local Moran's I
local_moran_MSOA_obesity_diet <- localmoran(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$obesity_ratio, nb_weights_list)


#First we will map the local moran statistic (Ii). A positive value for Ii indicates that the unit is surrounded by units with similar values.
# binds results to our polygon shapefile
moran.map <- MSOA_obesity_diet_sp
moran.map@data<- cbind(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp@data, local_moran_MSOA_obesity_diet)
# maps the results
tm_shape(moran.map) + tm_fill("Ii", style = "quantile", title = "local moran statistic") 

#From the map it is possible to see the variations in autocorrelation across space. We can interpret that there seems to be a geographic pattern to the autocorrelation.
tm_shape(moran.map) + tm_fill("Pr(z > 0)", style = "quantile", title = "local moran statistic p value") 

#From the local moran statistic p value, it is possible to see P-value to observe variances in significance across London.


# rescale
MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$scale_obesity_ratio <- scale(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$obesity_ratio) 

# create a spatial lag variable 
MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$lag_scale_obesity_ratio <- lag.listw(nb_weights_list, MSOA_obesity_diet_sp$scale_obesity_ratio)

# convert to sf
MSOA_obesity_diet_sp_stats <- st_as_sf(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp)

# classification without significance value

'high-high', 
                                       ifelse(MSOA_obesity_diet_sp_stats$scale_obesity_ratio <= 0 &

# plot the results without the statistical significance

3.2 Point pattern analysis

our data are not existing grobal spatially clustered. To detect patterns across a set of locations, including measuring density, dispersion and homogeneity in our data point structures by density-based methods

Therfore, we used k-means clustering to cluster the creation of a geodemographic to identify london regions with simalar new case. K-means clustering aims to partition a set of observations into a number of clusters (k), in which each observation will be assigned to the cluster with the nearest mean. As such, a cluster refers to a collection of data points aggregated together because of certain similarities. In order to run a k-means clustering, you first define a target number k of clusters that you want. The k-means algorithm subsequently assigns every observation to one of the clusters by finding the solution that minimises the total within-cluster variance.

#An object of the class ppp represents a two-dimensional point data set within a pre-defined area
# transform sf to sp
MSOA_sp <- as(MSOA,'Spatial')

# get the window of observation using maptools package
window <- as.owin.SpatialPolygons(MSOA_sp)

# inspect
window
## window: polygonal boundary
## enclosing rectangle: [503574.2, 561956.7] x [155850.8, 200933.61] units
# get coordinates from sf object
obesity_diet_points_coords <- matrix(unlist(MSOA_obesity_diet$geometry),ncol=2,byrow=T)

# inspect
head(obesity_diet_points_coords)

# add some jitter to our points

# count the number of duplicated points
any(duplicated(obesity_diet_ppp_jitter))
## [1] FALSE
# quadratcount in a 15 x 15 grid across the observational window
obesity_diet_quadrat <- quadratcount(obesity_diet_ppp_jitter,nx=15,ny=15)

# inspect
plot(obesity_diet_quadrat)

As we want to know whether or not there is any kind of spatial pattern present in our data, we need to look at our data and ask again whether the pattern is generated in a random manner; i.e. whether the distribution of points in our study area differs from complete spatial randomness (CSR) or whether there are some clusters present. We can do test some quadrats have higher counts than others by using a Poisson point process.

# create and plot a completely spatially random point pattern of the same size as our data
plot(rpoispp(1254))

The first thing you will see is that the points are not uniformly distributed. Furthermore, every time you run the function the outcome will be slightly different than the previous time because the points are sampled from a Poisson distribution. To check whether new cocid-19 case points differ from complete spatial randomness (i.e. there is no clustering or dispersal of points) we can run a [Chi-Squared test] with the null hypotheses that our point data have been generated under complete spatial randomness.

# chi-square between observed pattern and Poisson sampled points
quadrat.test(obesity_diet_ppp_jitter,nx=15,ny=15)
## 
##  Chi-squared test of CSR using quadrat counts
## 
## data:  obesity_diet_ppp_jitter
## X2 = 2529.8, df = 163, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
## 
## Quadrats: 164 tiles (irregular windows)

NOTE: The p value is well below 0.05 ( p-value < 2.2e-16), and we can reject the null hypothesis: our point pattern was not generated in a random matter. Not very surprising.

# kernel density estimation with a 100 metre bandwidth
plot(density.ppp(obesity_diet_ppp_jitter,sigma=100))

# kernel density estimation with a 500 metre bandwidth
plot(density.ppp(obesity_diet_ppp_jitter,sigma=500))

# kernel density estimation with a 1000 metre bandwidth
plot(density.ppp(obesity_diet_ppp_jitter,sigma=1000))

bandwidth typically has a more pronounced effect upon the density estimation than the type of kernel used, kernel types can affect the result too. Also here applies: the selection of the kernel depends on how much you want to weigh near points relative to far points (even though this is also influenced by the bandwidth!).

# kernel density estimation with a Gaussian Kernel
plot(density.ppp(obesity_diet_ppp_jitter,sigma=500,kernel='gaussian'))

# kernel density estimation with a Quartic Kernel
plot(density.ppp(obesity_diet_ppp_jitter,sigma=500,kernel='quartic'))

# kernel density estimation with an Epanechnikov Kernel
plot(density.ppp(obesity_diet_ppp_jitter,sigma=500,kernel='epanechnikov'))

Bandwidth typically has a more marked effect upon the density estimation than kernel type and is defined as the extent of the area around each grid cell from which the occurrences, and their respective kernels, are drawn.

For now, however, no matter which kernel or which bandwidth (within reason, of course) we use, we can be quite confident in stating that obesity in London is not a spatially random process and we can clearly see the areas where cases is most concentrated.
